<collectingCountry box="[1040,1165,509,534]" name="Guatemala" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="231" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,257,1038]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,545,570]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">Etymology.</emphasis>
Gender feminine. “Tri” is Greek for three, in reference to the three vibrant colors defining this genus (red, yellow, and blue). “-chromis” is Greek for fish.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="231" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,257,1038]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,617,642]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">Comments.</emphasis>
This species of northern Middle American cichlid has been recovered in several different phylogenetic positions across studies. Most of these discrepancies are likely due to differences in taxonomic sampling among studies. 
<bibRefCitation box="[441,718,689,714]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" refString="Matamoros, W. A., McMahan, C. D., Chakrabarty, P., Albert, J. S. &amp; Schaefer, J. F. (2015) Derivation of the freshwater fish fauna of Central America revisited: Myers's hypothesis in the twenty-first century. Cladistics, 31 (2), 177 - 188. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12081" type="journal article">
Matamoros 
<emphasis box="[577,628,689,714]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[651,710,689,714]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" value="2015.0">2015</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recovered this species outside of the herichthyins and sister to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,421,725,750]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Cryptoheros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanoluteus">
<emphasis box="[151,421,725,750]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">Cryptoheros nanoluteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[436,650,725,750]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" refString="Rican, O., Pialek, L., Zardoya, R., Doadrio, I. &amp; Zrzav, Y. (2013) Biogeography of the Mesoamerican Cichlidae (Teleostei: Heroini): colonization through the GAARlandia land bridge and early diversification. Journal of Biogeography, 40 (3), 579 - 593. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / jbi. 12023" type="journal article">
Říčan 
<emphasis box="[509,560,725,750]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[583,642,726,750]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" value="2013.0">2013</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recovered this species as the sister group to 
<taxonomicName box="[1159,1293,725,750]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Thorichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1159,1293,725,750]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">Thorichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and López- Fernández 
<emphasis box="[276,326,761,786]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[350,409,762,786]" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" value="2010.0">2010</number>
) found this species to be outside of the herichthyin cichlids and the sister group to a large clade of several different genera. In nearly all cases (including the present study), 
<taxonomicName box="[1072,1175,797,822]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Trichromis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="20" pageNumber="231" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="salvini">
<emphasis box="[1072,1085,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1100,1175,797,822]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="231">salvini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recovered in its own clade and not the sister group to any species or clade of species even remotely similar morphologically. Thus, given the phylogenetic position and the morphological distinctiveness of this species, we describe a new genus to contain this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
